{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f2a049f1-a043-47be-96d5-5f805eadff5a","content":"Here's the essential data to collect:\n\n**1. Heap dumps (most critical)**\n```bash\n# Take 2+ dumps spaced apart to compare growth\ndotnet-dump collect -p <PID>\n```\n\n**2. GC metrics over time**\n```bash\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nWatch: `gc_heap_size`, `gen2_size`, `loh_size`, `gc_count`.\n\n**3. Trace for allocation sources**\n```bash\ndotnet-gcdump collect -p <PID>\n```\nLightweight alternative showing surviving object graphs.\n\n**4. Native memory (if managed heap looks fine)**\n```bash\npmap -x <PID>   # snapshot RSS breakdown\ndotnet-dump analyze dump.dmp\n> eeheaps        # managed vs native split\n```\n\n**Analysis workflow:**\n1. Compare two `dotnet-dump` files with `dumpheap -stat` — look for object types with growing counts.\n2. Use `gcroot <address>` on suspicious objects to find what's holding references.\n3. If managed heap is stable but RSS grows, suspect native leaks (HttpClient, unmanaged resources) — use `createdump` + native profilers.\n\n**Quick checklist of common .NET 8 culprits:**\n- Event handler subscriptions never removed\n- Static collections/caches without eviction\n- Undisposed `HttpClient` / `IDisposable` objects\n- Timer callbacks capturing references","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"591b5548-b757-4250-a647-380ecbcbc937","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about diagnosing a memory leak in a .NET 8 application running on a Linux VM. This is a knowledge/advice question - I don't need to search a codebase or make changes. I should provide a concise, actionable answer about what data to collect.","outputTokens":432,"requestId":"5038:2C79E8:1FEA17:27476B:69F55076"},"id":"0fef71f0-63a6-4682-891b-f5f7dba4fc40","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:16:50.466Z","parentId":"0eadd9d5-d4da-4542-a8ca-b2190ea357f7"}
